<TITLE> Japan's emperor to cut back on official duties </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Thu Jan 29, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Japan's Emperor Akihito, 75, will cut back on his official duties after suffering stress-related health problems at the end of last year, the Imperial Household Agency said on Thursday. Akihito, who underwent surgery for prostate cancer in 2003, will cut the number of speeches he gives, reduce the number of foreign dignitaries he meets and hand over responsibility for some palace rituals to officials, the agency said on its website. "We have been considering official duties and rituals with a view to reducing the burden on their majesties and have now come up with a summary of the results of these deliberations," the agency said. Akihito has been carrying out many more official duties than his father, Emperor Hirohito, did at the same age, it said. Some tabloids have hit out at his eldest son, Crown Prince Naruhito, and his wife, Crown Princess Masako, for failing to take on more of the burden of public appearances. Masako, a former diplomat, has been suffering from a mental disorder caused by the difficulty of adjusting to the restrictions of palace life, which has kept her largely out of the public eye for five years. bdnews24.com/lq/2054 hrs. Akihito this month marks 20 years on the throne and later this year the 50th anniversary of his marriage to Empress Michiko. The changes to the palace schedule are also aimed at benefiting Michiko, 74, who has suffered health woes of her own, including digestive problems and dizziness. "She sometimes experiences symptoms that we must interpret as a kind of warning from 
